# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: borovička
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:borovička/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:borovička/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:borovička/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:borovička/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:borovička/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:borovička/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:borovička/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:borovička/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:borovička/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:borovička/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:borovička/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:borovička/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:borovička/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:borovička/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:borovička/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:borovička/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:borovička/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:borovička/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:borovička/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:borovička/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:borovička/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:borovička/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:borovička/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:borovička/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:borovička/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:borovička/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:borovička/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:borovička/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:borovička/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:borovička/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:borovička/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:borovička/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:borovička/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:borovička/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:borovička/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:borovička/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:borovička/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:borovička/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:borovička/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:borovička/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:borovička/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:borovička/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:borovička/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:borovička/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:borovička/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:borovička/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:borovička/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:borovička/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:borovička/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:borovička/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:borovička/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:borovička/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:borovička/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:borovička/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:borovička/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:borovička/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:borovička/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:borovička/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:borovička/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:borovička/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:borovička/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:borovička/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:borovička/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:borovička/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:borovička/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:borovička/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:borovička/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:borovička/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:borovička/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:borovička/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:borovička/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:borovička/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:borovička/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:borovička/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:borovička/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:borovička/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:borovička/acerum] In the 1970s, distillers began to produce alcohol from maple syrup.
[src:borovička/acerum] Although some distilled alcohol tests were then carried out in university laboratories, it was not until the 1990s that certain maple syrup producers began to produce a wine based on this sweet resource, which was initially called Acer.
[src:borovička/acerum] One of the first producers of Acerum was The Domaine Acer, based in Témiscouata, Quebec.
[src:borovička/acerum] When Vallier Robert took the reins of his family maple business in 1990, he quickly saw the potential to make alcohol.
[src:borovička/acerum] In 1996, the maple farmer was granted the first licence to produce artisanal maple-based alcoholic beverages.
[src:borovička/acerum] He began creating several varieties of maple sap wine, including dry, sparkling and dessert wines.
[src:borovička/acerum] During the same period, some distilleries began to market maple eau-de-vie, but it was not until December 2017 that the name Acerum appeared for the first time for a maple eau-de-vie.
[src:borovička/acerum] As defined by the specifications of the UDSÉ, Acerum must be entirely manufactured in the province of Quebec, in Canada, with maple syrup, maple concentrate, or maple sap from Quebec maples.
[src:borovička/advocaat] Two theories have been put out on the origins of "advocaat".
[src:borovička/advocaat] According to several makers, such as Verpoorten and Bols, and the *Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets*, its origins can be traced back to "abacate", an alcoholic beverage of the indigenous people in Brazil, which was made with avocado.
[src:borovička/advocaat] Dutch colonials of northern Brazil introduced this beverage to Europe as "advocat/advocaat".
[src:borovička/advocaat] As avocados could not grow in northern Europe, they were replaced with egg yolk, thought to have a similar taste and consistency, and the name derived from the avocado stuck, although the drink no longer contains any.
[src:borovička/advocaat] Cooymans started a distillery in downtown 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:borovička/advocaat] There he developed the egg drink "advocaat".
[src:borovička/advocaat] In 1876, the Antwerp distiller Eugen Verpoorten established a distillery in Heinsberg near Aachen, Germany, which made an egg liqueur (*Eierlikör* in German) using eggs, sugar, distilled alcohol, and other ingredients.
[src:borovička/advocaat] Jars and wide mouth bottles of thick advocaat are sold mainly in the Netherlands and Belgium, though may be available in Germany, Austria, and South Africa.
[src:borovička/advocaat] Further exports are of a more liquid version.
[src:borovička/advocaat] In particular the original thick variety, i.e., without albumen, is used as a waffle, pancake or poffertjes topping, as an ingredient in ice cream, custards, pastries and similar desserts, or as an apéritif or digestif.
[src:borovička/advocaat] The latter, possibly topped with whipped cream and then occasionally sprinkled with a touch of cocoa powder, is served in a very tiny bowl or small glass from which it is eaten by use of a teaspoon.
[src:borovička/advocaat] In Belgian restaurants and taverns, it may be a complementary accompaniment to a coffee.
[src:borovička/advocaat] In the export variety both parts of the eggs are used.
[src:borovička/advocaat] A popular cocktail using advocaat is the Snowball: a mixture of advocaat, sparkling lemonade and sometimes (although this is not required) lime juice that is often consumed at Christmas time.
[src:borovička/advocaat] Another is the Fluffy duck, made with rum.
[src:borovička/advocaat] Another advocaat-based beverage is the Bombardino, a drink commonly found in Italian ski resorts, particularly the Italian Alps, made by mixing advocaat, brandy, and whipped cream.
[src:borovička/advocaat] The Polish equivalent, *ajerkoniak* (German: *eier* 'eggs' and French: *cognac*), is based on vodka instead of brandy, despite what the name may suggest.
[src:borovička/agave] Many plants in this genus may be considered perennial, because they require several to many years to mature and flower.
[src:borovička/agave] However, most *Agave* species are more accurately described as monocarpic rosettes or multiannuals, since each individual rosette flowers only once and then dies; a small number of *Agave* species are polycarpic.
[src:borovička/agave] Along with plants from the closely related genera *Yucca*, *Hesperoyucca*, and *Hesperaloe,* various *Agave* species are popular ornamental plants in hot, dry climates, as they require very little supplemental water to survive.
[src:borovička/agave] Some *Agave* species are known by the common name "century plant".
[src:borovička/agave] In other regions, it goes by different names.
[src:borovička/agave] In the Chinese, Japanese, and Korean languages, it is referred to as the compound word *dragon tongue orchid* (simplified Chinese: 龙舌兰; traditional Chinese: 龍舌蘭; pinyin: *lóngshélán*; Japanese: 竜舌蘭, romanized: *ryūzetsuran*; Korean: 용설란; Hanja: 龍舌蘭; RR: *yongseollan*).
[src:borovička/agave] In Malta, it is referred to as *Sabbara*; In Maltese, Agave americana is referred to as "Sabbara tal-Amerika", and Agave sisalana is referred to as "Sabbara ta' Sisal".
[src:borovička/agave] The succulent leaves of most *Agave* species have sharp marginal teeth, an extremely sharp terminal spine, and are very fibrous inside.
[src:borovička/agave] The stout stem is usually extremely short, which may make the plant appear as though it is stemless.
[src:borovička/agave] Agaves can be confused with cacti, aloes, or stonecrops, but although these plants all share similar morphological adaptations to arid environments (e.g. succulence), each group belongs to a different plant family and probably experienced convergent evolution.
[src:borovička/agave] Further, cactus (Cactaceae) and stonecrop (Crassulaceae) lineages are eudicots, while aloes (Asphodelaceae) and agaves (Asparagaceae) are monocots.
[src:borovička/agave] The agave root system, consisting of a network of shallow rhizomes, allows the agave to efficiently capture moisture from rain, condensation, and dew.
[src:borovička/agave] In addition to growing from seeds, most agaves produce 'pups' – young plants from runners.
[src:borovička/agave] *Agave vilmoriniana* (the octopus agave) produces hundreds of pups on its bloom stalk.
[src:borovička/agave] Agave leaves store the plant's water and are crucial to its continued existence.
[src:borovička/agave] The coated leaf surface prevents evaporation.
[src:borovička/agave] The leaves also have sharp, spiked edges.
[src:borovička/agave] The spikes discourage predators from eating the plant or using it as a source of water and are so tough that ancient peoples used them for sewing needles.
[src:borovička/agave] Some agaves bloom at a height up to 9 m (30 ft) so that they are far out of reach to animals that might attack them.
[src:borovička/agave] Smaller species, such as *Agave lechuguilla*, have smaller bloom stalks.
[src:borovička/agave] The genus name *Agave* come from the Ancient Greek αγαυή *agauê* from ἀγαυός *agauós* meaning "illustrious, noble" having to do with very tall flower spikes found on its many species.
[src:borovička/agave] The genus *Agave* was erected by Carl Linnaeus in 1753, initially with four species.
[src:borovička/agave] The first listed was *Agave americana*, now the type species.
[src:borovička/agave] In the Cronquist system and others, *Agave* was placed in the family Liliaceae, but phylogenetic analyses of DNA sequences later showed it did not belong there.
[src:borovička/agave] In the APG II system, *Agave* was placed in the segregated family Agavaceae.
[src:borovička/agave] When this system was superseded by the APG III system in 2009, the Agavaceae were subsumed into the expanded family Asparagaceae, and *Agave* was treated as one of 18 genera in the subfamily Agavoideae, a position retained in the APG IV system of 2016.
[src:borovička/agave] However, Agavaceae had regained its taxonomic status as an independent family by 2020.
[src:borovička/agave] Agaves and close relatives have long presented significant taxonomic difficulty.
[src:borovička/agave] These difficulties could be due to the relatively young evolutionary age of the group (major diversification events of the group most likely occurred 8–10 million years ago), ease of hybridization between species (and even genera), incomplete lineage sorting, and long generation times.
[src:borovička/agave] Within a species, morphological variations can be considerable, especially in cultivation; many named species may be variants of original wild-type species that horticulturalists bred to appear unique in cultivation.
[src:borovička/agave] With the advent of DNA sequencing, new karyologic and evolutionary phylogenetic studies showed that the genera *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* were genetically nested within the traditional circumscription of *Agave*, rendering the genus paraphyletic.
[src:borovička/agave] Early in the 21st century, these new phylogenetic results led to a reclassification of to include *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* together as *Agave* subgenus *Manfreda*.
[src:borovička/agave] There was reaction against the changes from those who noted that the large morphological differences between the genera in this new *Agave* s.l. making them "counter-intuitive from a horticultural point of view".
[src:borovička/agave] *Manfreda* morphologically differs from the classic *Agave* description in being herbaceous and bulbous, while *Polianthes* are deciduous with narrow leaves and no spines.
[src:borovička/agave] Mexican taxonomists have continued to adhere to the traditional classifications and have published new species of *Polianthes*.
[src:borovička/agave] Thus, based on a wider consideration of previously established genetic, morphological, and estimated genetic divergence times, Vázquez-García et al. proposed a narrower circumscription of *Agave* by creating three new genera: *Echinoagave*, *Paleoagave* and *Paraagave*.
[src:borovička/agave] These new genera have gained some acceptance, and pave the way for a reconsideration of *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes*.
[src:borovička/agave] Some commonly grown species include *Agave americana*, *A. angustifolia*, *A. attenuata*, *A. murpheyi*, *A. palmeri*, *A. parryi*, *A. parviflora*, *A. tequilana*, *A. victoriae-reginae*, and *A. vilmoriniana*.
[src:borovička/agave] One of the most familiar species is *A. americana*, a native of tropical America.
[src:borovička/agave] Common names include century plant, *maguey* (in Mexico), or American aloe (though not related to the genus *Aloe*).
[src:borovička/agave] The name "century plant" refers to the long time the plant takes to flower.
[src:borovička/agave] The number of years before flowering occurs depends on the vigor of the individual plant, the richness of the soil, and the climate; during these years, the plant is storing in its fleshy leaves the nourishment required for the effort of flowering.
[src:borovička/agave] Some species contain components in their juice which can cause dermatitis for some people.
[src:borovička/agave] The ethnobotany of the agave was described by William H.
[src:borovička/agave] The four major edible parts of the agave are the flowers, the leaves, the stalks or basal rosettes, and the sap (in Spanish: *aguamiel*, meaning "honey water").
[src:borovička/agave] The sap of some species can also be used as soap.
[src:borovička/agave] Each agave plant produces several pounds of edible flowers during its final season.
[src:borovička/agave] The stalks, which are ready during the summer, before the blossom, weigh several pounds each.
[src:borovička/agave] Roasted, they are sweet and can be chewed to extract the sap or *aguamiel*, like sugarcane.
[src:borovička/agave] When dried out, the stalks can be used to make didgeridoos.
[src:borovička/agave] The leaves may be collected in winter and spring, when the plants are rich in sap, for eating.
[src:borovička/agave] The leaves of several species also yield fiber, for instance, *A. sisalana*, the sisal hemp, and *A. decipiens*, the false sisal hemp.
[src:borovička/agave] *A. americana* is the source of pita fiber, and is used as a fiber plant in Mexico, the West Indies, and southern Europe.
[src:borovička/agave] The agave, especially *A. murpheyi*, was a major food source for the prehistoric indigenous people of the Southwestern United States.
[src:borovička/agave] The Hohokam of southern Arizona cultivated large areas of agave.
[src:borovička/agave] The Navajo similarly found many uses for the agave plant.
[src:borovička/agave] A beverage is squeezed from the baked fibers, and the heads can be baked or boiled, pounded into flat sheets, sun dried, and stored for future use.
[src:borovička/agave] The baked, dried heads are also boiled and made into an edible paste, eaten whole, or made into soup.
[src:borovička/agave] The leaves are eaten boiled, and the young, tender flowering stalks and shoots are roasted and eaten as well.
[src:borovička/agave] The fibers are used to make rope, the leaves are used to line baking pits, and the sharp-pointed leaf tips are used to make basketry awls.
[src:borovička/agave] During the development of the inflorescence, sap rushes to the base of the young flower stalk.
[src:borovička/agave] Agave syrup (commonly called agave nectar), a sweetener derived from the sap, is used as an alternative to sugar in cooking, and can be added to breakfast cereals as a binding agent.
[src:borovička/agave] Extracts from agave leaves are under preliminary research for their potential use as food additives.
[src:borovička/agave] The sap of *A. americana* and other species is used in Mexico and Mesoamerica to produce pulque, an alcoholic beverage.
[src:borovička/agave] The flower shoot is cut out and the sap collected and subsequently fermented.
[src:borovička/agave] By distillation, a spirit called mezcal is prepared; one of the best-known forms of mezcal is tequila.
[src:borovička/agave] *azul* is used in the production of tequila.
[src:borovička/agave] *A. angustifolia* is widely used in the production of mezcal and pulque, though at least 10 other *Agave* species are also known to be used for this.
[src:borovička/agave] Agave can be used as the raw material for industrial production of fructans as a prebiotic dietary fiber.
[src:borovička/agave] Agave contains fructooligosaccharides, which are naturally occurring oligosaccharides that support safely subjecting peanut-allergic people to allergen immunotherapy.
[src:borovička/agave] Resulting from its natural habitat in stressful environments, agave is under preliminary research for its potential use in germplasm conservation and in biotechnology to better anticipate the economic effects of global climate change.
[src:borovička/agave] It may also have use as a bioethanol or bioenergy feedstock.
[src:borovička/agave] Agave plantations have potential applications on marginal lands unsuitable for grain crops.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] The word is a compound of the Iberian languages' words for 'water' (*agua* in Castilian, i.e.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Spanish; *aigua* in Catalan; *água* in Portuguese; *auga* in Galician) and 'burning'/'fiery' (*ardiente* in Castilian; *ardent* in Catalan; *ardente* in Portuguese and Galician).
[src:borovička/aguardiente] A comparable word in English is "firewater", though the English term is colloquial or humorous, whereas *aguardiente* is stylistically neutral in Spanish.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] However, *aguardiente* and *aguardente* are not legal denominations.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Instead, different categories of *aguardientes* (spirits in the English version) are established according to raw materials.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In the Spanish version, wine spirit (brandy) is *aguardiente de vino*, fruit spirit is *aguardiente de fruta*, grain spirit (other than whiskey and neutral grain spirit) is *aguardiente de cereales*, etc.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Some drinks named *aguardiente* or similar are of different origins (grape pomace, sugarcane); other drinks with the same origin may have different names (clairin, brandy).
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In Brazil, a beverage known as *cachaça* or *pinga*, considered distinct from traditional *aguardiente*, is made from sugarcane.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] *Cachaça* has two varieties: unaged (white) and aged (gold).
[src:borovička/aguardiente] White *cachaça* is usually bottled immediately after distillation and tends to be cheaper.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] It is often used to prepare caipirinha and other beverages in which *cachaça* is an ingredient.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Dark *cachaça*, usually seen as the "premium" variety, is aged in wood barrels and is meant to be drunk neat.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Traditionally, no herbs are used to flavor the *cachaça*; its flavor is influenced by the fermentation agent, time spent in the cask, or the type of wood from which the barrel is made.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] One form that can be qualified as moonshine is known as "Maria Louca" ("Crazy Mary").
[src:borovička/aguardiente] This is *aguardiente*, made in jails by inmates.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] It can be made from many cereals, ranging from beans to rice, or whatever can be converted into alcohol, be it fruit peels or candy, using improvised and illegal equipment.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Grogue, also known as grogu or grogo (derived from English grog), is a Cape Verdean alcoholic beverage, an *aguardiente* made from sugarcane processed in a trapiche.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Its production is fundamentally artisanal, and nearly all the sugarcane is used in producing grogue.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In Chile, *aguardiente* is an alcoholic beverage of 45% and higher ABV (beverages with over 55% ABV are illegal).
[src:borovička/aguardiente] It is made, like Italian grappa, by distilling the grape residue, primarily the skins and pulp (**hollejo**) plus the stems (**escobajos**) and seeds, left over from winemaking after pressing the grapes.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] It is used to make several other flavored liquors, such as the *murtado* or **enmurtillado** (using sun-dried *murtilla*, an orange-reddish wild rose fruit), the **enguindado** (soaking sun-dried morello cherries) and *licor de oro* (flavored with saffron and lemon peel).
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Dried mint, peeled walnuts, almonds, and other aromatic herbs are also used to flavor the *aguardiente*.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] It is mainly consumed by itself or as a base to make *cola de mono* ("monkey tail").
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In Colombia, *aguardiente* is an anise-flavored liqueur derived from sugarcane, popular in the Andean region.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Different flavors are obtained by adding different amounts of aniseed, leading to extensive marketing and fierce competition between brands.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] *Aguardiente* has 24%–29% alcohol content.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Other anise-flavored liqueurs similar to *aguardiente*, but with a lower alcohol content, are also sold.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Since the Spanish era, *aguardiente* has maintained the status of the most popular alcoholic beverage in the Andean regions of Colombia, with the notable exception of the Caribbean region, where rum is most popular.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Generally, *aguardiente* is rarely drunk in cocktails and usually drunk neat.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] On the Caribbean coast, there is a moonshine called "Cococho", an *aguardiente* infamous for the number of blindness cases due to the addition of methanol.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In Costa Rica, it is 30% alcohol, with a neutral flavor.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] The Costa Rican government tightly controls Guaro to help prevent clandestine production.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In Guam and the Mariana Islands, a distilled version of *tubâ* (coconut palm wine introduced from the Philippines) is known as *aguajente* (also *aguayente* or *agi*).
[src:borovička/aguardiente] It was prevalent among the Chamorro people, but is largely extinct; the United States banned its manufacture soon after the acquisition of Guam from the Spanish Empire in 1899.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] A local company "Aguayente distillers" has recently installed a commercial still and will soon start distilling liquor from locally grown potatoes.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In Ecuador, *aguardiente* is also derived from sugar cane, but unlike Colombia, it is left largely unflavoured.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] It is then taken straight as shots, mulled with cinnamon (*canela* in Spanish) and fruit juices to make the hot cocktail *canelazo*, or mixed with the juice of naranjilla and spices for the hot cocktail *draquita*.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Locally or artisanally made *aguardiente* is commonly called *punta*, "puro" or *trago*, and alcohol content can vary widely, from "mild" *puntas* of about 10% to "strong" of about 40% or higher.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] The traditional distillation process produces *aguardiente* as strong as 60 g/L.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Every Ecuadorian province has a slightly different flavor to the *aguardiente* made there, and each province has a different recipe for *canelazo*.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In Ecuador, *aguardiente* is the most commonly consumed strong alcohol.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In Mexico, *aguardiente* goes by many names, including *habanero*.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In the state of Michoacán, *charanda* is a traditional rum-like sugar cane *aguardiente*.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Casa Berreteaga marketed an *aguardiente* called "Berreteaga", which used sugarcane sourced from the Coxcatlan region of Puebla.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Berreteaga was a fortified wine made from rum and sweet wine (usually Muscat) or (uncommonly) a sweet brandy that was then aged in oak barrels.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Portuguese *aguardente* has several varieties.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] *Aguardente vínica* is distilled from either good quality or undrinkable wine.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] It is mostly used to fortify wines such as port or aged to make *aguardente velha* (old burning water), a kind of brandy.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] *Aguardente bagaceira* (mostly known as "bagaço") is made from pomace to prevent waste after the close of wine season.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] It is usually bootlegged, as most drinkers only appreciate it in its traditional formulation of 50% to 80% ABV.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] A common way to drink it is as *café com cheirinho* ("coffee with a little scent"), a liqueur coffee made with espresso.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In the Azores, this *espresso-aguardente* combination is commonly referred to as *café com música* ("coffee with music").
[src:borovička/aguardiente] *Aguardente Medronho* is a variety distilled from the fruit of the *Arbutus unedo* tree.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In Madeira, it is the core ingredient for *poncha*, a beverage around which a festival is based.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Most of the *aguardente* from the region is made from sugarcane.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In certain areas of the Pyrenees in Catalonia, *aiguardent*, as it is known in Catalan, is used as an essential ingredient in the preparation of *tupí*, a type of cheese.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Galicia is renowned for the quality and variety of its *augardentes* (Galician), or *aguardientes* (Spanish), including *augardente de bagazo* (*aguardiente de Orujo*), which is obtained from the distillation of the pomace of grapes, and is clear and colorless.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] It typically contains over 50% alcohol, sometimes significantly more, and is still made traditionally in many villages across Galicia today.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] *Augardente de herbas*, usually yellow, is a sweet liqueur made with *augardente de bagazo* and herbs (*herbas*), with chamomile being a substantial ingredient.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] *Licor café* (typical distilled drink in the province of Ourense), black in color, is a sweet liqueur made with *augardente de bagazo*, coffee (*café*), and sugar.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] *Crema de augardente* or c*rema de caña* is a cream liqueur based on *augardente*, coffee, cream, milk, and other ingredients.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] In some places in Galicia, a small glass is traditionally taken at breakfast as a tonic before a hard day's work on the land.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] The word "*orujo*" is Spanish and not Galician, but is used to distinguish Galician and some Spanish augardentes from those of other countries.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Most of the moonshine in Spain is made as a byproduct of winemaking by distilling the squeezed skins of the grapes.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] The essential product is called "*orujo*" or "*aguardiente*" (burning water).
[src:borovička/aguardiente] The homemade versions are usually more potent and have a higher alcoholic content, well over the 40% that the commercial versions typically have.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] It is often mixed with herbs, spices, fruits, or other distillates.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] Types include *pacharán*, *licor de café* and *orujo de hierbas* (tea mixed with orujo).
[src:borovička/aguardiente] During the mission and rancho periods of California history, *aguardiente* was made out of mission grapes.
[src:borovička/aguardiente] It was popular during the Gold Rush of 1849.
[src:borovička/akvavit] The word *aquavit* derives from the Latin *aqua vitae*, "water of life." Compare the words *whisky* and *whiskey*, from Gaelic *uisce beatha*, which has the same meaning.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Likewise, clear fruit brandy is called *eau de vie* (French for "water of life").
[src:borovička/akvavit] Akvavit is an important part of Nordic drinking culture, where it is often drunk during festive gatherings, such as Christmas dinners and the Midsummer celebration, and as an aperitif.
[src:borovička/akvavit] In Iceland, Sweden, Denmark, and Germany, aquavit is chilled and often drunk in a single gulp from a small shot glass.
[src:borovička/akvavit] This is usually attributed to tradition.
[src:borovička/akvavit] In Norway, it is not generally chilled, but enjoyed slowly.
[src:borovička/akvavit] In Sweden, aquavit is commonly consumed immediately following a song, called a snapsvisa.
[src:borovička/akvavit] The most well-known song is "Helan Går".
[src:borovička/akvavit] In Finland and Sweden, aquavit consumed from a shot glass is also commonly associated with crayfish parties, which are traditionally held during late August.
[src:borovička/akvavit] In Denmark, aquavit is called snaps or akvavit, and is primarily consumed in December during Christmas lunches or around Easter during Easter lunches.
[src:borovička/akvavit] It is consumed year-round, though, mainly for lunches of traditional Danish dishes where beer is also always on the table.
[src:borovička/akvavit] In Norway, where most aquavit is matured in oak casks, the drink is served at room temperature in tulip-shaped glasses.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Aquavit arguably complements beer well, and its consumption is very often preceded by a swig of beer.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Akvavit must be distilled from an agricultural base, most commonly grain or potatoes.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Similarly to gin, it is flavoured with botanicals.
[src:borovička/akvavit] The dominant flavours must be caraway or dill, or sometimes both.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Swedish Akvavit must also contain fennel in order to be labelled as such.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Other common botanicals include cardamom, cumin, anise, and coriander.
[src:borovička/akvavit] The Danish distillery Aalborg makes an akvavit distilled with amber, which imparts a pine-like citrusy note.
[src:borovička/akvavit] The Aalborg brand is now produced in Norway by Arcus Group.
[src:borovička/akvavit] The recipes and flavours differ between brands, with each brand's unique characteristics coming from distillation methods and supporting botanicals in their blends.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Un-aged Akvavit is clear, while aged Akvavit typically has a pale straw-to-golden hue, depending on how long it has been aged in oak casks (most common in Norway) or the amount of colourant used.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Normally, a darker colour suggests a higher age or the use of young casks, although artificial caramel colouring and infusing fruits or botanicals for colour and flavour are permitted before bottling.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Clear akvavit is often called *taffel*, meaning table aquavit.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Taffel aquavit is typically aged in old casks that do not colour the finished spirit, or it is not aged at all.
[src:borovička/akvavit] The earliest known reference to "aquavit" is found in a 1531 letter from the Lord of Bergenshus castle, (Norway) Eske Bille, to Olav Engelbrektsson, the last Roman Catholic Archbishop of Norway.
[src:borovička/akvavit] The letter, dated April 13 and accompanying a package, offers the archbishop "some water which is called Aqua Vite and is a help for all sort of illness which a man can have both internally and externally".
[src:borovička/akvavit] While this claim for the medicinal properties of the drink may be rather inflated, aquavit is popularly believed to ease the digestion of rich foods.
[src:borovička/akvavit] In Norway, it is drunk at celebrations, particularly Christmas, Easter, or May 17 (Norwegian Constitution Day).
[src:borovička/akvavit] In Denmark, it is traditionally associated with Christmas and Easter lunches.
[src:borovička/akvavit] In Sweden, it is a staple of the traditional midsummer celebrations dinner, usually drunk while singing one of many drinking songs.
[src:borovička/akvavit] It is usually drunk as snaps during meals, especially during the appetizer course — along with pickled herring, crayfish, lutefisk, or smoked fish.
[src:borovička/akvavit] In this regard, it is popularly quipped that aquavit helps the fish swim down to the stomach.
[src:borovička/akvavit] It is also a regular in traditional Norwegian Christmas meals, including roasted rib of pork and rib of lamb (*pinnekjøtt*).
[src:borovička/akvavit] The spices and the alcohol are said to help digest the meal, which is very rich in fat.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Among the most important brands are Løiten, Lysholm, Opland, and Simers from Norway; Aalborg and Brøndum from Denmark; and O.P.
[src:borovička/akvavit] While the Danish and Swedish variants are normally very light in colour, most of the Norwegian brands are matured in oak casks for at least six months, and for some brands even as long as 12 years, making them generally darker in colour.
[src:borovička/akvavit] While members of all three nations can be found to claim that "their" style of aquavit is the best as a matter of national pride, Swedish *akvavit* is typically the most renowned around the world, specifically so in the culinary scene.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Whilst the Norwegian *akevitt* tends to have if not the most distinctive character, then at least the most overpowering flavour and deepest colour due to the aging process.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Peculiar to the Norwegian tradition are *Linje Aquavits* (such as "Løiten Linie" and "Lysholm Linie").
[src:borovička/akvavit] Linje Aquavit is named after the tradition of sending oak barrels of aquavit with ships from Norway to Australia and back again, thereby passing the equator ("linje") twice before being bottled.
[src:borovička/akvavit] The constant movement, high humidity, and fluctuating temperature cause the spirit to extract more flavour and contribute to accelerated maturation.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Norwegian aquavit distillers Anora (formerly Arcus) carried out a test where they tried to emulate the rocking of the casks aboard the "Linje" ships while the oak barrels were subjected to the weather elements, as they would aboard a ship.
[src:borovička/akvavit] The finished product was, according to Anora, far from the taste that a proper *linje* aquavit should have.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Therefore, to this day, boats loaded with "Linie Aquavit" set sail from Norway to Australia and back again before they are bottled and sold as part of the Norwegian Christmas traditions, but also enjoyed all year round.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Aquavit was seldom produced outside of the Nordic countries, but that began to change dramatically starting around 2010, especially in the United States, and particularly in areas that have larger concentrations of people with a Nordic heritage.
[src:borovička/akvavit] An exception, however, is Northern Germany, and in particular the German state of Schleswig-Holstein, which was part of Denmark until the 19th century (see History of Schleswig-Holstein) and still has a notable Danish minority.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Among the most important German brands are Bommerlunder from Flensburg, Kieler Sprotte from Kiel, and Malteserkreuz.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Malteserkreuz has been produced in Berlin since 1924 by a subsidiary of Sweden's Vin & Sprit AB (now Pernod Ricard), the producer of many Swedish akvavits, and can be considered a German imitation of the Nordic aquavits since it is based on an original Danish recipe.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Brands from Schleswig-Holstein, however, often have a long history, comparable to their Nordic counterparts.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Bommerlunder, for instance, has been made since 1760.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Aquavit is also an important part of the traditional cuisine of Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:borovička/akvavit] German aquavit is virtually always distilled from fermented grain and generally has an alcohol content of 38% by volume, marginally less than Scandinavian aquavits.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Many distilleries in the United States produce aquavit, especially in parts of the country with high populations of people of Nordic heritage.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Examples include Colorado, Minnesota, Michigan, Wisconsin, Montana, Illinois, Oregon, New Hampshire, and Washington.
[src:borovička/akvavit] The Midwest states in particular do quite well for the category and have produced numerous internationally acclaimed/award-winning brands.
[src:borovička/akvavit] See List of Akvavit Producers in the United States for brand names and distilleries.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Aquavit is also seeing a rise in popularity in Canada, particularly in Scandinavian settlements.
[src:borovička/akvavit] Notable brands include Spirit of York Co in Toronto, Ontario, Drum Distilling Co in Drumheller, Alberta, and The Newfoundland Distillery Co, in Clarkes Beach Newfoundland.
[src:borovička/borovička] Today's commercially produced borovička typically contains about 40% alcohol by volume or 80 proof, but can reach as high as 50 to 70% alcohol content.
[src:borovička/borovička] As a benchmark, the minimum alcohol amount required by law in Slovakia is 35%.
[src:borovička/borovička] Its flavour, although much stronger, resembles that of gin.
[src:borovička/borovička] The production process consists of a two-stage distillation that in general uses only ripe berries from Juniperus communis and Juniperus oxycedrus.
[src:borovička/borovička] Similar, but differently made drinks known in south Slavic countries include brinjevec in Slovenia (*brin* means juniper in Slovene) and klekovača in Serbia (*kleka* means juniper in Serbian).
[src:borovička/borovička] Other similar drinks include several types of gin like Jenever.
[src:borovička/borovička] International Juniper Brandy Day is celebrated annually on 24 June.
[src:borovička/borovička] According to *The Dictionary of the Slovak Language*, *borovička* derives its name from the Slovak word for juniper, *borievka*.
[src:borovička/borovička] Borovička harks back to the 16th century, when this beverage was produced in the Habsburg monarchy's county of Liptov, today part of central Slovakia.
[src:borovička/borovička] It was exported throughout the whole Habsburg monarchy, particularly to Vienna and Budapest.
[src:borovička/borovička] It was transported southward principally via rafts floating down the river Váh.
[src:borovička/borovička] *"37,5% nivnicka borovicka 0,5l, Traditional spirits - LINEA NIVNICE, a.s." Archived from the original on 2007-09-29.
